I have a couple of questions about these quotes. 

&amp;#x200B;

First, what is the total kW DC size of each system? Here in Georgia, you need special permission from the utility company to install above a 10 kW AC system, and you need to sign an agreement that you can never feed power back to the grid. With the IQ7s, your system has the potential to produce exactly 10 kW AC, which makes it a large system, but not too far out of the ordinary. The other system, however, has the potential to produce 18 kW AC, which seems excessive for a residential system.

&amp;#x200B;

Now without knowing the size of the modules, I cannot determine how much clipping might occur, but I have a feeling there may be a decent amount of clipping from the Canadian Solar panels. I don't sell the IQ7s anymore because the panels we install require a larger inverter. 

&amp;#x200B;

Also, regardless of kW size, the encharge 10 can only support 23 modules using the IQ7's, so that means the rest of your system would feed directly into the grid, and you would be losing all excess power or selling it back to the utility company. If you use enough energy to require that amount of solar, then one battery will not get you very far. 

&amp;#x200B;

These companies have also likely quoted you a financed price, and they've hidden the dealer fee into the price of the solar. The financing company may pay the company as little as 75% of the contract price to the solar installer.  If you were to tell them that you were paying cash, they would likely give you a "discount" of 10-15%. You can ask what the dealer fee for the financing is, but they'll likely not tell you. Also, the larger company may have a cheaper financing option than the smaller company. Honestly, adding up battery, solar, and dealer fee, these prices seem like they might be fair, but I don't know your market.

&amp;#x200B;

Really, the best way to compare pricing is to subtract the battery cost, and then to compare the price per watt for the solar. Energysage can give you a good range to expect in price per watt for your area, and then you can find a solar company in your area with good reviews that can provide that for you. 

&amp;#x200B;

Best of luck!
